After clever move 32, this one is a tactical blunder. The last white pawn could wait; it certainly wasn't going anywhere. 35. ... Rg2! forces a rook trade after 36. ... Rb1. Getting rid of white's last piece (even at an even trade) would have been preferable to chasing a mere pawn.

Now if 37. Re1+ then 37. ... Kd3 puts an end to white. If 38. Re7 threatening pawns, black simply plays 38. ... Rf1+ 39. Re1 Rxe1 40. Kxe1 and white is done - black promotes a pawn and checkmates soon after. But at this point my opponent timed out, so the game remains unfinished. After 84 days for 36 moves, I can't say I'm too disappointed - the outcome was already decided anyway.
